 114 @tf_export("math.abs", "abs")
 115 def abs(x, name=None):  # pylint: disable=redefined-builtin
 116   r"""Computes the absolute value of a tensor.
 117 
 118   Given a tensor `x` of complex numbers, this operation returns a tensor of type
 119   `float32` or `float64` that is the absolute value of each element in `x`. All
 120   elements in `x` must be complex numbers of the form \\(a + bj\\). The
 121   absolute value is computed as \\( \sqrt{a^2 + b^2}\\).  For example:
 122   ```python
 123   x = tf.constant([[-2.25 + 4.75j], [-3.25 + 5.75j]])
 124   tf.abs(x)  # [5.25594902, 6.60492229]
 125   ```
 126 
 127   Args:
 128     x: A `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` of type `float16`, `float32`, `float64`,
 129       `int32`, `int64`, `complex64` or `complex128`.
 130     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 131 
 132   Returns:
 133     A `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` the same size and type as `x` with absolute
 134       values.
 135     Note, for `complex64` or `complex128` input, the returned `Tensor` will be
 136       of type `float32` or `float64`, respectively.
 137   """
 138   with ops.name_scope(name, "Abs", [x]) as name:
 139     if isinstance(x, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
 140       if x.values.dtype.is_complex:
 141         x_abs = gen_math_ops.complex_abs(
 142             x.values, Tout=x.values.dtype.real_dtype, name=name)
 143         return sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(
 144             indices=x.indices, values=x_abs, dense_shape=x.dense_shape)
 145       x_abs = gen_math_ops._abs(x.values, name=name)
 146       return sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(
 147           indices=x.indices, values=x_abs, dense_shape=x.dense_shape)
 148     else:
 149       x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
 150       if x.dtype.is_complex:
 151         return gen_math_ops.complex_abs(x, Tout=x.dtype.real_dtype, name=name)
 152       return gen_math_ops._abs(x, name=name)

 166 class DivideDelegateWithName(object):
 167   """Use Python2/Python3 division delegation to implement divide for tensors."""
 168 
 169   def __init__(self, x, name):
 170     """Construct DivideDelegateWithName.
 171 
 172     Args:
 173       x: Tensor to use as left operand in operator overloads
 174       name: The name that is preferred for the op created.
 175     """
 176     self.x = x
 177     self.name = name
 178 
 179   def __truediv__(self, y):
 180     return _truediv_python3(self.x, y, self.name)
 181 
 182   def __floordiv__(self, y):
 183     return floordiv(self.x, y, self.name)
 184 
 185   def __div__(self, y):
 186     return _div_python2(self.x, y, self.name)
 187 
 188 
 189 @tf_export("math.divide", "divide")
 190 def divide(x, y, name=None):
 191   """Computes Python style division of `x` by `y`."""
 192 
 193   if name is not None:
 194     # Cannot use tensors operator overload, because it has no way to track
 195     # override names. Use a dummy class to track the runtime division behavior
 196     return DivideDelegateWithName(x, name) / y
 197   else:
 198     return x / y

 291 @tf_export("math.sign", "sign")
 292 def sign(x, name=None):
 293   """Returns an element-wise indication of the sign of a number.
 294 
 295   `y = sign(x) = -1` if `x < 0`; 0 if `x == 0` or `tf.is_nan(x)`; 1 if `x > 0`.
 296 
 297   Zero is returned for NaN inputs.
 298 
 299   For complex numbers, `y = sign(x) = x / |x|` if `x != 0`, otherwise `y = 0`.
 300 
 301   Args:
 302     x: A `Tensor` or `SparseTensor`. Must be one of the following types: `half`,
 303       `float32`, `float64`, `int32`, `int64`, `complex64`, `complex128`.
 304     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 305 
 306   Returns:
 307     A `Tensor` or `SparseTensor`, respectively. Has the same type as `x`.
 308 
 309   @compatibility(numpy)
 310   Equivalent to numpy.sign except for the behavior for input values of NaN.
 311   @end_compatibility
 312   """
 313   with ops.name_scope(name, "Sign", [x]) as name:
 314     if isinstance(x, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
 315       x_sign = gen_math_ops.sign(x.values, name=name)
 316       return sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(
 317           indices=x.indices, values=x_sign, dense_shape=x.dense_shape)
 318     else:
 319       return gen_math_ops.sign(x, name=name)

 390 @tf_export("math.scalar_mul", "scalar_mul")
 391 def scalar_mul(scalar, x):
 392   """Multiplies a scalar times a `Tensor` or `IndexedSlices` object.
 393 
 394   Intended for use in gradient code which might deal with `IndexedSlices`
 395   objects, which are easy to multiply by a scalar but more expensive to
 396   multiply with arbitrary tensors.
 397 
 398   Args:
 399     scalar: A 0-D scalar `Tensor`. Must have known shape.
 400     x: A `Tensor` or `IndexedSlices` to be scaled.
 401 
 402   Returns:
 403     `scalar * x` of the same type (`Tensor` or `IndexedSlices`) as `x`.
 404 
 405   Raises:
 406     ValueError: if scalar is not a 0-D `scalar`.
 407   """
 408   scalar = ops.convert_to_tensor(
 409       scalar, dtype=x.dtype.base_dtype, name="scalar")
 410   shape = scalar.get_shape()
 411   if shape.ndims == 0:
 412     if isinstance(x, ops.IndexedSlices):
 413       return ops.IndexedSlices(scalar * x.values, x.indices, x.dense_shape)
 414     else:
 415       return scalar * x
 416   else:
 417     raise ValueError("Only scalar multiply works, got shape %s" % shape)
 418

 420 @tf_export("math.pow", "pow")
 421 def pow(x, y, name=None):  # pylint: disable=redefined-builtin
 422   r"""Computes the power of one value to another.
 423 
 424   Given a tensor `x` and a tensor `y`, this operation computes \\(x^y\\) for
 425   corresponding elements in `x` and `y`. For example:
 426 
 427   ```python
 428   x = tf.constant([[2, 2], [3, 3]])
 429   y = tf.constant([[8, 16], [2, 3]])
 430   tf.pow(x, y)  # [[256, 65536], [9, 27]]
 431   ```
 432 
 433   Args:
 434     x: A `Tensor` of type `float16`, `float32`, `float64`, `int32`, `int64`,
 435      `complex64`, or `complex128`.
 436     y: A `Tensor` of type `float16`, `float32`, `float64`, `int32`, `int64`,
 437      `complex64`, or `complex128`.
 438     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 439 
 440   Returns:
 441     A `Tensor`.
 442   """
 443   with ops.name_scope(name, "Pow", [x]) as name:
 444     return gen_math_ops._pow(x, y, name=name)

 447 # pylint: disable=redefined-builtin,redefined-outer-name
 448 @tf_export("dtypes.complex", "complex")
 449 def complex(real, imag, name=None):
 450   r"""Converts two real numbers to a complex number.
 451 
 452   Given a tensor `real` representing the real part of a complex number, and a
 453   tensor `imag` representing the imaginary part of a complex number, this
 454   operation returns complex numbers elementwise of the form \\(a + bj\\), where
 455   *a* represents the `real` part and *b* represents the `imag` part.
 456 
 457   The input tensors `real` and `imag` must have the same shape.
 458 
 459   For example:
 460 
 461   ```python
 462   real = tf.constant([2.25, 3.25])
 463   imag = tf.constant([4.75, 5.75])
 464   tf.complex(real, imag)  # [[2.25 + 4.75j], [3.25 + 5.75j]]
 465   ```
 466 
 467   Args:
 468     real: A `Tensor`. Must be one of the following types: `float32`,
 469       `float64`.
 470     imag: A `Tensor`. Must have the same type as `real`.
 471     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 472 
 473   Returns:
 474     A `Tensor` of type `complex64` or `complex128`.
 475   """
 476   real = ops.convert_to_tensor(real, name="real")
 477   imag = ops.convert_to_tensor(imag, name="imag")
 478   with ops.name_scope(name, "Complex", [real, imag]) as name:
 479     input_types = (real.dtype, imag.dtype)
 480     if input_types == (dtypes.float64, dtypes.float64):
 481       Tout = dtypes.complex128
 482     elif input_types == (dtypes.float32, dtypes.float32):
 483       Tout = dtypes.complex64
 484     else:
 485       raise TypeError("real and imag have incorrect types: "
 486                       "{} {}".format(real.dtype.name, imag.dtype.name))
 487     return gen_math_ops._complex(real, imag, Tout=Tout, name=name)
 488

 490 @tf_export("math.real", "real")
 491 @deprecation.deprecated_endpoints("real")
 492 def real(input, name=None):
 493   r"""Returns the real part of a complex (or real) tensor.
 494 
 495   Given a tensor `input`, this operation returns a tensor of type `float` that
 496   is the real part of each element in `input` considered as a complex number.
 497 
 498   For example:
 499 
 500   ```python
 501   x = tf.constant([-2.25 + 4.75j, 3.25 + 5.75j])
 502   tf.real(x)  # [-2.25, 3.25]
 503   ```
 504 
 505   If `input` is already real, it is returned unchanged.
 506 
 507   Args:
 508     input: A `Tensor`. Must have numeric type.
 509     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 510 
 511   Returns:
 512     A `Tensor` of type `float32` or `float64`.
 513   """
 514   with ops.name_scope(name, "Real", [input]) as name:
 515     if input.dtype.is_complex:
 516       real_dtype = input.dtype.real_dtype
 517       return gen_math_ops.real(input, Tout=real_dtype, name=name)
 518     else:
 519       return input

 522 @tf_export("math.imag", "imag")
 523 @deprecation.deprecated_endpoints("imag")
 524 def imag(input, name=None):
 525   r"""Returns the imaginary part of a complex (or real) tensor.
 526 
 527   Given a tensor `input`, this operation returns a tensor of type `float` that
 528   is the imaginary part of each element in `input` considered as a complex
 529   number. If `input` is real, a tensor of all zeros is returned.
 530 
 531   For example:
 532 
 533   ```python
 534   x = tf.constant([-2.25 + 4.75j, 3.25 + 5.75j])
 535   tf.imag(x)  # [4.75, 5.75]
 536   ```
 537 
 538   Args:
 539     input: A `Tensor`. Must be one of the following types: `float`, `double`,
 540       `complex64`, `complex128`.
 541     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 542 
 543   Returns:
 544     A `Tensor` of type `float32` or `float64`.
 545   """
 546   with ops.name_scope(name, "Imag", [input]) as name:
 547     if input.dtype.is_complex:
 548       return gen_math_ops.imag(input, Tout=input.dtype.real_dtype, name=name)
 549     else:
 550       return array_ops.zeros_like(input)

 557 
 558   Given a tensor `input`, this operation returns a tensor of type `float` that
 559   is the argument of each element in `input` considered as a complex number.
 560 
 561   The elements in `input` are considered to be complex numbers of the form
 562   \\(a + bj\\), where *a* is the real part and *b* is the imaginary part.
 563   If `input` is real then *b* is zero by definition.
 564 
 565   The argument returned by this function is of the form \\(atan2(b, a)\\).
 566   If `input` is real, a tensor of all zeros is returned.
 567 
 568   For example:
 569 
 570   ```
 571   # tensor 'input' is [-2.25 + 4.75j, 3.25 + 5.75j]
 572   tf.angle(input) ==> [2.0132, 1.056]
 573   ```
 574 
 575   Args:
 576     input: A `Tensor`. Must be one of the following types: `float`, `double`,
 577       `complex64`, `complex128`.
 578     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 579 
 580   Returns:
 581     A `Tensor` of type `float32` or `float64`.
 582   """
 583   with ops.name_scope(name, "Angle", [input]) as name:
 584     if input.dtype.is_complex:
 585       return gen_math_ops.angle(input, Tout=input.dtype.real_dtype, name=name)
 586     else:
 587       return array_ops.zeros_like(input)

 593 @tf_export("math.round", "round")
 594 def round(x, name=None):  # pylint: disable=redefined-builtin
 595   """Rounds the values of a tensor to the nearest integer, element-wise.
 596 
 597   Rounds half to even.  Also known as bankers rounding. If you want to round
 598   according to the current system rounding mode use tf::cint.
 599   For example:
 600 
 601   ```python
 602   x = tf.constant([0.9, 2.5, 2.3, 1.5, -4.5])
 603   tf.round(x)  # [ 1.0, 2.0, 2.0, 2.0, -4.0 ]
 604   ```
 605 
 606   Args:
 607     x: A `Tensor` of type `float16`, `float32`, `float64`, `int32`, or `int64`.
 608     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 609 
 610   Returns:
 611     A `Tensor` of same shape and type as `x`.
 612   """
 613   x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
 614   if x.dtype.is_integer:
 615     return x
 616   else:
 617     return gen_math_ops.round(x, name=name)

 620 @tf_export("dtypes.cast", "cast")
 621 def cast(x, dtype, name=None):
 622   """Casts a tensor to a new type.
 623 
 624   The operation casts `x` (in case of `Tensor`) or `x.values`
 625   (in case of `SparseTensor` or `IndexedSlices`) to `dtype`.
 626 
 627   For example:
 628 
 629   ```python
 630   x = tf.constant([1.8, 2.2], dtype=tf.float32)
 631   tf.cast(x, tf.int32)  # [1, 2], dtype=tf.int32
 632   ```
 633 
 634   The operation supports data types (for `x` and `dtype`) of
 635   `uint8`, `uint16`, `uint32`, `uint64`, `int8`, `int16`, `int32`, `int64`,
 636   `float16`, `float32`, `float64`, `complex64`, `complex128`, `bfloat16`.
 637   In case of casting from complex types (`complex64`, `complex128`) to real
 638   types, only the real part of `x` is returned. In case of casting from real
 639   types to complex types (`complex64`, `complex128`), the imaginary part of the
 640   returned value is set to `0`. The handling of complex types here matches the
 641   behavior of numpy.
 642 
 643   Args:
 644     x: A `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` or `IndexedSlices` of numeric type. It could
 645       be `uint8`, `uint16`, `uint32`, `uint64`, `int8`, `int16`, `int32`,
 646       `int64`, `float16`, `float32`, `float64`, `complex64`, `complex128`,
 647       `bfloat16`.
 648     dtype: The destination type. The list of supported dtypes is the same as
 649       `x`.
 650     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 651 
 652   Returns:
 653     A `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` or `IndexedSlices` with same shape as `x` and
 654       same type as `dtype`.
 655 
 656   Raises:
 657     TypeError: If `x` cannot be cast to the `dtype`.
 658   """
 659   base_type = dtypes.as_dtype(dtype).base_dtype
 660   if isinstance(x,
 661                 (ops.Tensor, _resource_variable_type)) and base_type == x.dtype:
 662     return x
 663   with ops.name_scope(name, "Cast", [x]) as name:
 664     if isinstance(x, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
 665       values_cast = cast(x.values, base_type, name=name)
 666       x = sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(x.indices, values_cast, x.dense_shape)
 667     elif isinstance(x, ops.IndexedSlices):
 668       values_cast = cast(x.values, base_type, name=name)
 669       x = ops.IndexedSlices(values_cast, x.indices, x.dense_shape)
 670     else:
 671       # TODO(josh11b): If x is not already a Tensor, we could return
 672       # ops.convert_to_tensor(x, dtype=dtype, ...)  here, but that
 673       # allows some conversions that cast() can't do, e.g. casting numbers to
 674       # strings.
 675       x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
 676       if x.dtype.base_dtype != base_type:
 677         x = gen_math_ops.cast(x, base_type, name=name)
 678     if x.dtype.is_complex and base_type.is_floating:
 679       logging.warn("Casting complex to real discards imaginary part.")
 680     return x

 683 @tf_export("dtypes.saturate_cast", "saturate_cast")
 684 def saturate_cast(value, dtype, name=None):
 685   """Performs a safe saturating cast of `value` to `dtype`.
 686 
 687   This function casts the input to `dtype` without applying any scaling.  If
 688   there is a danger that values would over or underflow in the cast, this op
 689   applies the appropriate clamping before the cast.
 690 
 691   Args:
 692     value: A `Tensor`.
 693     dtype: The desired output `DType`.
 694     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 695 
 696   Returns:
 697     `value` safely cast to `dtype`.
 698   """
 699   # When casting to a type with smaller representable range, clamp.
 700   # Note that this covers casting to unsigned types as well.
 701   with ops.name_scope(name, "saturate_cast", [value]) as name:
 702     value = ops.convert_to_tensor(value, name="value")
 703     dtype = dtypes.as_dtype(dtype).base_dtype
 704     if value.dtype.min < dtype.min:
 705       value = gen_math_ops.maximum(value,
 706                                    ops.convert_to_tensor(
 707                                        dtype.min, dtype=value.dtype,
 708                                        name="min"))
 709     if value.dtype.max > dtype.max:
 710       value = gen_math_ops.minimum(value,
 711                                    ops.convert_to_tensor(
 712                                        dtype.max, dtype=value.dtype,
 713                                        name="max"))
 714     return cast(value, dtype, name=name)

 851 def _OverrideBinaryOperatorHelper(func, op_name, clazz_object=ops.Tensor):
 852   """Register operators with different tensor and scalar versions.
 853 
 854   If `clazz_object` is `SparseTensor`, assumes `func` takes `(sp_indices,
 855   sp_values, sp_shape, dense)` and outputs `(new_sp_values)`.
 856 
 857   Args:
 858     func: the operator
 859     op_name: name of the operator being overridden
 860     clazz_object: class to override for.  Either `Tensor` or `SparseTensor`.
 861   """
 862 
 863   def binary_op_wrapper(x, y):
 864     with ops.name_scope(None, op_name, [x, y]) as name:
 865       if isinstance(x, ops.Tensor) and isinstance(y, ops.Tensor):
 866         return func(x, y, name=name)
 867       elif not isinstance(y, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
 868         try:
 869           y = ops.convert_to_tensor(y, dtype=x.dtype.base_dtype, name="y")
 870         except TypeError:
 871           # If the RHS is not a tensor, it might be a tensor aware object
 872           # that can implement the operator with knowledge of itself
 873           # and the tensor.
 874           if hasattr(type(y), "__r%s__" % op_name):
 875             return NotImplemented
 876           else:
 877             raise
 878       return func(x, y, name=name)
 879 
 880   def binary_op_wrapper_sparse(sp_x, y):
 881     with ops.name_scope(None, op_name, [sp_x, y]) as name:
 882       y = ops.convert_to_tensor(y, dtype=sp_x.dtype.base_dtype, name="y")
 883       return sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(sp_x.indices,
 884                                         func(
 885                                             sp_x.indices,
 886                                             sp_x.values,
 887                                             sp_x.dense_shape,
 888                                             y,
 889                                             name=name), sp_x.dense_shape)
 890 
 891   def r_binary_op_wrapper(y, x):
 892     with ops.name_scope(None, op_name, [x, y]) as name:
 893       x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, dtype=y.dtype.base_dtype, name="x")
 894       return func(x, y, name=name)
 895 
 896   # Propagate func.__doc__ to the wrappers
 897   try:
 898     doc = func.__doc__
 899   except AttributeError:
 900     doc = None
 901   binary_op_wrapper.__doc__ = doc
 902   r_binary_op_wrapper.__doc__ = doc
 903   binary_op_wrapper_sparse.__doc__ = doc
 904 
 905   if clazz_object is ops.Tensor:
 906     clazz_object._override_operator("__%s__" % op_name, binary_op_wrapper)
 907     del binary_op_wrapper
 908     clazz_object._override_operator("__r%s__" % op_name, r_binary_op_wrapper)
 909     del r_binary_op_wrapper
 910   else:
 911     clazz_object._override_operator("__%s__" % op_name,
 912                                     binary_op_wrapper_sparse)
 913     del binary_op_wrapper_sparse

 916 # Conversion table for __truediv__.  None entries mean no conversion required.
 917 _TRUEDIV_TABLE = {
 918     dtypes.uint8: dtypes.float32,
 919     dtypes.int8: dtypes.float32,
 920     dtypes.uint16: dtypes.float32,
 921     dtypes.int16: dtypes.float32,
 922     dtypes.int32: dtypes.float64,
 923     dtypes.int64: dtypes.float64,
 924     dtypes.bfloat16: None,
 925     dtypes.float16: None,
 926     dtypes.float32: None,
 927     dtypes.float64: None,
 928     dtypes.complex64: None,
 929     dtypes.complex128: None,
 930 }

 933 # NOTE: the support of "sparse (true)div dense" is currently not baked in into
 934 # "tf.(true_)div()".  Until such an API decision is made, the supported usage is
 935 # to explicitly use the "/" operator to invoke either truediv or div.
 936 def _sparse_dense_truediv(sp_indices, sp_values, sp_shape, y, name=None):
 937   """Internal helper function for 'sp_t / dense_t'."""
 938   with ops.name_scope(name, "truediv",
 939                       [sp_indices, sp_values, sp_shape, y]) as name:
 940     sp_values = ops.convert_to_tensor(sp_values, name="sp_values")
 941     y = ops.convert_to_tensor(y, name="y")
 942     x_dtype = sp_values.dtype.base_dtype
 943     y_dtype = y.dtype.base_dtype
 944     if x_dtype != y_dtype:
 945       raise TypeError("x and y must have the same dtype, got %r != %r" %
 946                       (x_dtype, y_dtype))
 947     try:
 948       dtype = _TRUEDIV_TABLE[x_dtype]
 949     except KeyError:
 950       raise TypeError("Invalid dtype %r in __truediv__" % x_dtype)
 951     if dtype is not None:
 952       sp_values = cast(sp_values, dtype)
 953       y = cast(y, dtype)
 954     return gen_sparse_ops.sparse_dense_cwise_div(
 955         sp_indices, sp_values, sp_shape, y, name=name)

 958 def _truediv_python3(x, y, name=None):
 959   with ops.name_scope(name, "truediv", [x, y]) as name:
 960     x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
 961     y = ops.convert_to_tensor(y, name="y")
 962     x_dtype = x.dtype.base_dtype
 963     y_dtype = y.dtype.base_dtype
 964     if x_dtype != y_dtype:
 965       raise TypeError("x and y must have the same dtype, got %r != %r" %
 966                       (x_dtype, y_dtype))
 967     try:
 968       dtype = _TRUEDIV_TABLE[x_dtype]
 969     except KeyError:
 970       raise TypeError("Invalid dtype %r in __truediv__" % x_dtype)
 971     if dtype is not None:
 972       x = cast(x, dtype)
 973       y = cast(y, dtype)
 974     return gen_math_ops.real_div(x, y, name=name)

 977 def _div_python2(x, y, name=None):
 978   """Divide two values using Python 2 semantics. Used for Tensor.__div__.
 979 
 980   Args:
 981     x: `Tensor` numerator of real numeric type.
 982     y: `Tensor` denominator of real numeric type.
 983     name: A name for the operation (optional).
 984   Returns:
 985     `x / y` returns the quotient of x and y.
 986   """
 987 
 988   with ops.name_scope(name, "div", [x, y]) as name:
 989     x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
 990     y = ops.convert_to_tensor(y, name="y", dtype=x.dtype.base_dtype)
 991     x_dtype = x.dtype.base_dtype
 992     y_dtype = y.dtype.base_dtype
 993     if x_dtype != y_dtype:
 994       raise TypeError("x and y must have the same dtype, got %r != %r" %
 995                       (x_dtype, y_dtype))
 996     if x_dtype.is_floating or x_dtype.is_complex:
 997       return gen_math_ops.real_div(x, y, name=name)
 998     else:
 999       return gen_math_ops.floor_div(x, y, name=name)

1002 @tf_export("math.truediv", "truediv")
1003 def truediv(x, y, name=None):
1004   """Divides x / y elementwise (using Python 3 division operator semantics).
1005 
1006   NOTE: Prefer using the Tensor operator or tf.divide which obey Python
1007   division operator semantics.
1008 
1009   This function forces Python 3 division operator semantics where all integer
1010   arguments are cast to floating types first.   This op is generated by normal
1011   `x / y` division in Python 3 and in Python 2.7 with
1012   `from __future__ import division`.  If you want integer division that rounds
1013   down, use `x // y` or `tf.math.floordiv`.
1014 
1015   `x` and `y` must have the same numeric type.  If the inputs are floating
1016   point, the output will have the same type.  If the inputs are integral, the
1017   inputs are cast to `float32` for `int8` and `int16` and `float64` for `int32`
1018   and `int64` (matching the behavior of Numpy).
1019 
1020   Args:
1021     x: `Tensor` numerator of numeric type.
1022     y: `Tensor` denominator of numeric type.
1023     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1024 
1025   Returns:
1026     `x / y` evaluated in floating point.
1027 
1028   Raises:
1029     TypeError: If `x` and `y` have different dtypes.
1030   """
1031   return _truediv_python3(x, y, name)

1034 @tf_export("div")
1035 def div(x, y, name=None):
1036   """Divides x / y elementwise (using Python 2 division operator semantics).
1037 
1038   NOTE: Prefer using the Tensor division operator or tf.divide which obey Python
1039   division operator semantics.
1040 
1041   This function divides `x` and `y`, forcing Python 2.7 semantics. That is,
1042   if one of `x` or `y` is a float, then the result will be a float.
1043   Otherwise, the output will be an integer type. Flooring semantics are used
1044   for integer division.
1045 
1046   Args:
1047     x: `Tensor` numerator of real numeric type.
1048     y: `Tensor` denominator of real numeric type.
1049     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1050   Returns:
1051     `x / y` returns the quotient of x and y.
1052   """
1053   return _div_python2(x, y, name)

1056 @tf_export("div_no_nan")
1057 def div_no_nan(x, y, name=None):
1058   """Computes an unsafe divide which returns 0 if the y is zero.
1059 
1060   Args:
1061     x: A `Tensor`. Must be one of the following types: `float32`, `float64`.
1062     y: A `Tensor` whose dtype is compatible with `x`.
1063     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1064   Returns:
1065     The element-wise value of the x divided by y.
1066   """
1067 
1068   with ops.name_scope(name, "div_no_nan", [x, y]) as name:
1069     x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
1070     y = ops.convert_to_tensor(y, name="y", dtype=x.dtype.base_dtype)
1071     x_dtype = x.dtype.base_dtype
1072     y_dtype = y.dtype.base_dtype
1073     if x_dtype != y_dtype:
1074       raise TypeError("x and y must have the same dtype, got %r != %r" %
1075                       (x_dtype, y_dtype))
1076     return gen_math_ops.div_no_nan(x, y, name=name)

1085 @tf_export("math.floordiv", "floordiv")

1087 def floordiv(x, y, name=None):
1088   """Divides `x / y` elementwise, rounding toward the most negative integer.
1089 
1090   The same as `tf.div(x,y)` for integers, but uses `tf.floor(tf.div(x,y))` for
1091   floating point arguments so that the result is always an integer (though
1092   possibly an integer represented as floating point).  This op is generated by
1093   `x // y` floor division in Python 3 and in Python 2.7 with
1094   `from __future__ import division`.
1095 
1096   `x` and `y` must have the same type, and the result will have the same type
1097   as well.
1098 
1099   Args:
1100     x: `Tensor` numerator of real numeric type.
1101     y: `Tensor` denominator of real numeric type.
1102     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1103 
1104   Returns:
1105     `x / y` rounded down.
1106 
1107   Raises:
1108     TypeError: If the inputs are complex.
1109   """
1110   with ops.name_scope(name, "floordiv", [x, y]) as name:
1111     return gen_math_ops.floor_div(x, y, name=name)

1127 def _mul_dispatch(x, y, name=None):
1128   """Dispatches cwise mul for "Dense*Dense" and "Dense*Sparse"."""
1129   is_tensor_y = isinstance(y, ops.Tensor)
1130   if is_tensor_y:
1131     return gen_math_ops.mul(x, y, name=name)
1132   else:
1133     assert isinstance(y, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor)  # Case: Dense * Sparse.
1134     new_vals = gen_sparse_ops.sparse_dense_cwise_mul(y.indices, y.values,
1135                                                      y.dense_shape, x, name)
1136     return sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(y.indices, new_vals, y.dense_shape)

1180 @tf_export("range")
1181 def range(start, limit=None, delta=1, dtype=None, name="range"):  # pylint: disable=redefined-builtin
1182   """Creates a sequence of numbers.
1183 
1184   Creates a sequence of numbers that begins at `start` and extends by
1185   increments of `delta` up to but not including `limit`.
1186 
1187   The dtype of the resulting tensor is inferred from the inputs unless
1188   it is provided explicitly.
1189 
1190   Like the Python builtin `range`, `start` defaults to 0, so that
1191   `range(n) = range(0, n)`.
1192 
1193   For example:
1194 
1195   ```python
1196   start = 3
1197   limit = 18
1198   delta = 3
1199   tf.range(start, limit, delta)  # [3, 6, 9, 12, 15]
1200 
1201   start = 3
1202   limit = 1
1203   delta = -0.5
1204   tf.range(start, limit, delta)  # [3, 2.5, 2, 1.5]
1205 
1206   limit = 5
1207   tf.range(limit)  # [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]
1208   ```
1209 
1210   Args:
1211     start: A 0-D `Tensor` (scalar). Acts as first entry in the range if
1212       `limit` is not None; otherwise, acts as range limit and first entry
1213       defaults to 0.
1214     limit: A 0-D `Tensor` (scalar). Upper limit of sequence,
1215       exclusive. If None, defaults to the value of `start` while the first
1216       entry of the range defaults to 0.
1217     delta: A 0-D `Tensor` (scalar). Number that increments
1218       `start`. Defaults to 1.
1219     dtype: The type of the elements of the resulting tensor.
1220     name: A name for the operation. Defaults to "range".
1221 
1222   Returns:
1223     An 1-D `Tensor` of type `dtype`.
1224 
1225   @compatibility(numpy)
1226   Equivalent to np.arange
1227   @end_compatibility
1228   """
1229   if limit is None:
1230     start, limit = 0, start
1231 
1232   with ops.name_scope(name, "Range", [start, limit, delta]) as name:
1233     start = ops.convert_to_tensor(start, dtype=dtype, name="start")
1234     limit = ops.convert_to_tensor(limit, dtype=dtype, name="limit")
1235     delta = ops.convert_to_tensor(delta, dtype=dtype, name="delta")
1236 
1237     # infer dtype if not explicitly provided
1238     if dtype is None:
1239       dtype_hierarchy = [
1240           dtypes.int32, dtypes.int64, dtypes.float32, dtypes.float64
1241       ]
1242       assert all(arg.dtype in dtype_hierarchy for arg in [start, limit, delta])
1243       inferred_dtype = max(
1244           [arg.dtype for arg in [start, limit, delta]],
1245           key=dtype_hierarchy.index)
1246 
1247       start = cast(start, inferred_dtype)
1248       limit = cast(limit, inferred_dtype)
1249       delta = cast(delta, inferred_dtype)
1250 
1251     return gen_math_ops._range(start, limit, delta, name=name)
1252 
1253 
1254 # Reduction operations
1255 def _ReductionDims(x, axis, reduction_indices):
1256   """Returns range(0, rank(x)) if reduction_indices is None."""
1257   # TODO(aselle): Remove this after deprecation
1258   if reduction_indices is not None:
1259     if axis is not None:
1260       raise ValueError("Can't specify both axis' and 'reduction_indices'.")
1261     axis = reduction_indices
1262   if axis is not None:
1263     return axis
1264   else:
1265     # Fast path: avoid creating Rank and Range ops if ndims is known.
1266     rank = common_shapes.rank(x)
1267     if rank is not None:
1268       return constant_op.constant(np.arange(rank), dtype=dtypes.int32)
1269     if (isinstance(x, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor) and
1270         x.dense_shape.get_shape().is_fully_defined()):
1271       rank = x.dense_shape.get_shape()[0].value  # sparse.dense_shape is 1-D.
1272       return constant_op.constant(np.arange(rank), dtype=dtypes.int32)
1273 
1274     # Otherwise, we rely on Range and Rank to do the right thing at run-time.
1275     return range(0, array_ops.rank(x))
1276

1278 def _may_reduce_to_scalar(keepdims, axis, reduction_indices, output):
1279   """Set a reduction's output shape to be a scalar if we are certain."""
1280   if not common_shapes.has_fully_defined_shape(output) and (not keepdims) and (
1281       axis is None) and (reduction_indices is None):
1282     output.set_shape(())
1283   return output

1286 @tf_export("math.reduce_sum", "reduce_sum")
1287 @deprecation.deprecated_args(
1288     None, "keep_dims is deprecated, use keepdims instead", "keep_dims")
1289 def reduce_sum(input_tensor,
1290                axis=None,
1291                keepdims=None,
1292                name=None,
1293                reduction_indices=None,
1294                keep_dims=None):
1295   """Computes the sum of elements across dimensions of a tensor.
1296 
1297   Reduces `input_tensor` along the dimensions given in `axis`.
1298   Unless `keepdims` is true, the rank of the tensor is reduced by 1 for each
1299   entry in `axis`. If `keepdims` is true, the reduced dimensions
1300   are retained with length 1.
1301 
1302   If `axis` is None, all dimensions are reduced, and a
1303   tensor with a single element is returned.
1304 
1305   For example:
1306 
1307   ```python
1308   x = tf.constant([[1, 1, 1], [1, 1, 1]])
1309   tf.reduce_sum(x)  # 6
1310   tf.reduce_sum(x, 0)  # [2, 2, 2]
1311   tf.reduce_sum(x, 1)  # [3, 3]
1312   tf.reduce_sum(x, 1, keepdims=True)  # [[3], [3]]
1313   tf.reduce_sum(x, [0, 1])  # 6
1314   ```
1315 
1316   Args:
1317     input_tensor: The tensor to reduce. Should have numeric type.
1318     axis: The dimensions to reduce. If `None` (the default),
1319       reduces all dimensions. Must be in the range
1320       `[-rank(input_tensor), rank(input_tensor))`.
1321     keepdims: If true, retains reduced dimensions with length 1.
1322     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1323     reduction_indices: The old (deprecated) name for axis.
1324     keep_dims: Deprecated alias for `keepdims`.
1325 
1326   Returns:
1327     The reduced tensor, of the same dtype as the input_tensor.
1328 
1329   @compatibility(numpy)
1330   Equivalent to np.sum apart the fact that numpy upcast uint8 and int32 to
1331   int64 while tensorflow returns the same dtype as the input.
1332   @end_compatibility
1333   """
1334   keepdims = deprecation.deprecated_argument_lookup("keepdims", keepdims,
1335                                                     "keep_dims", keep_dims)
1336   if keepdims is None:
1337     keepdims = False
1338 
1339   return _may_reduce_to_scalar(keepdims, axis, reduction_indices,
1340                                gen_math_ops._sum(
1341                                    input_tensor,
1342                                    _ReductionDims(input_tensor, axis,
1343                                                   reduction_indices),
1344                                    keepdims,
1345                                    name=name))

1348 @tf_export("math.count_nonzero", "count_nonzero")
1349 @deprecation.deprecated_args(
1350     None, "keep_dims is deprecated, use keepdims instead", "keep_dims")
1351 def count_nonzero(input_tensor,
1352                   axis=None,
1353                   keepdims=None,
1354                   dtype=dtypes.int64,
1355                   name=None,
1356                   reduction_indices=None,
1357                   keep_dims=None):
1358   """Computes number of nonzero elements across dimensions of a tensor.
1359 
1360   Reduces `input_tensor` along the dimensions given in `axis`.
1361   Unless `keepdims` is true, the rank of the tensor is reduced by 1 for each
1362   entry in `axis`. If `keepdims` is true, the reduced dimensions
1363   are retained with length 1.
1364 
1365   If `axis` has no entries, all dimensions are reduced, and a
1366   tensor with a single element is returned.
1367 
1368   **NOTE** Floating point comparison to zero is done by exact floating point
1369   equality check.  Small values are **not** rounded to zero for purposes of
1370   the nonzero check.
1371 
1372   For example:
1373 
1374   ```python
1375   x = tf.constant([[0, 1, 0], [1, 1, 0]])
1376   tf.count_nonzero(x)  # 3
1377   tf.count_nonzero(x, 0)  # [1, 2, 0]
1378   tf.count_nonzero(x, 1)  # [1, 2]
1379   tf.count_nonzero(x, 1, keepdims=True)  # [[1], [2]]
1380   tf.count_nonzero(x, [0, 1])  # 3
1381   ```
1382 
1383   **NOTE** Strings are compared against zero-length empty string `""`. Any
1384   string with a size greater than zero is already considered as nonzero.
1385 
1386   For example:
1387   ```python
1388   x = tf.constant(["", "a", "  ", "b", ""])
1389   tf.count_nonzero(x) # 3, with "a", "  ", and "b" as nonzero strings.
1390   ```
1391 
1392   Args:
1393     input_tensor: The tensor to reduce. Should be of numeric type, `bool`,
1394       or `string`.
1395     axis: The dimensions to reduce. If `None` (the default),
1396       reduces all dimensions. Must be in the range
1397       `[-rank(input_tensor), rank(input_tensor))`.
1398     keepdims: If true, retains reduced dimensions with length 1.
1399     dtype: The output dtype; defaults to `tf.int64`.
1400     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1401     reduction_indices: The old (deprecated) name for axis.
1402     keep_dims: Deprecated alias for `keepdims`.
1403 
1404   Returns:
1405     The reduced tensor (number of nonzero values).
1406   """
1407   keepdims = deprecation.deprecated_argument_lookup("keepdims", keepdims,
1408                                                     "keep_dims", keep_dims)
1409   if keepdims is None:
1410     keepdims = False
1411 
1412   with ops.name_scope(name, "count_nonzero", [input_tensor]):
1413     input_tensor = ops.convert_to_tensor(input_tensor, name="input_tensor")
1414     # A scalar of 'zero' is enough as `not_equal` will broadcast.
1415     zero = array_ops.zeros([], dtype=input_tensor.dtype)
1416     return cast(
1417         reduce_sum(
1418             # int64 reduction happens on GPU
1419             to_int64(gen_math_ops.not_equal(input_tensor, zero)),
1420             axis=axis,
1421             keepdims=keepdims,
1422             reduction_indices=reduction_indices),
1423         dtype=dtype)

1762 @tf_export("math.reduce_logsumexp", "reduce_logsumexp")
1763 @deprecation.deprecated_args(
1764     None, "keep_dims is deprecated, use keepdims instead", "keep_dims")
1765 def reduce_logsumexp(input_tensor,
1766                      axis=None,
1767                      keepdims=None,
1768                      name=None,
1769                      reduction_indices=None,
1770                      keep_dims=None):
1771   """Computes log(sum(exp(elements across dimensions of a tensor))).
1772 
1773   Reduces `input_tensor` along the dimensions given in `axis`.
1774   Unless `keepdims` is true, the rank of the tensor is reduced by 1 for each
1775   entry in `axis`. If `keepdims` is true, the reduced dimensions
1776   are retained with length 1.
1777 
1778   If `axis` has no entries, all dimensions are reduced, and a
1779   tensor with a single element is returned.
1780 
1781   This function is more numerically stable than log(sum(exp(input))). It avoids
1782   overflows caused by taking the exp of large inputs and underflows caused by
1783   taking the log of small inputs.
1784 
1785   For example:
1786 
1787   ```python
1788   x = tf.constant([[0., 0., 0.], [0., 0., 0.]])
1789   tf.reduce_logsumexp(x)  # log(6)
1790   tf.reduce_logsumexp(x, 0)  # [log(2), log(2), log(2)]
1791   tf.reduce_logsumexp(x, 1)  # [log(3), log(3)]
1792   tf.reduce_logsumexp(x, 1, keepdims=True)  # [[log(3)], [log(3)]]
1793   tf.reduce_logsumexp(x, [0, 1])  # log(6)
1794   ```
1795 
1796   Args:
1797     input_tensor: The tensor to reduce. Should have numeric type.
1798     axis: The dimensions to reduce. If `None` (the default),
1799       reduces all dimensions. Must be in the range
1800       `[-rank(input_tensor), rank(input_tensor))`.
1801     keepdims: If true, retains reduced dimensions with length 1.
1802     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1803     reduction_indices: The old (deprecated) name for axis.
1804     keep_dims: Deprecated alias for `keepdims`.
1805 
1806   Returns:
1807     The reduced tensor.
1808   """
1809   keepdims = deprecation.deprecated_argument_lookup("keepdims", keepdims,
1810                                                     "keep_dims", keep_dims)
1811   if keepdims is None:
1812     keepdims = False
1813   input_tensor = ops.convert_to_tensor(input_tensor)
1814   with ops.name_scope(name, "ReduceLogSumExp", [input_tensor]) as name:
1815     raw_max = reduce_max(
1816         input_tensor,
1817         axis=axis,
1818         reduction_indices=reduction_indices,
1819         keepdims=True)
1820     my_max = array_ops.stop_gradient(
1821         array_ops.where(
1822             gen_math_ops.is_finite(raw_max), raw_max,
1823             array_ops.zeros_like(raw_max)))
1824     result = gen_math_ops.log(
1825         reduce_sum(
1826             gen_math_ops.exp(gen_math_ops.sub(input_tensor, my_max)),
1827             axis,
1828             keepdims=keepdims,
1829             reduction_indices=reduction_indices))
1830     if not keepdims:
1831       my_max = array_ops.reshape(my_max, array_ops.shape(result))
1832     result = gen_math_ops.add(result, my_max)
1833     return _may_reduce_to_scalar(keepdims, axis, reduction_indices, result)

1836 @tf_export("linalg.trace", "trace")
1837 @deprecation.deprecated_endpoints("trace")
1838 def trace(x, name=None):
1839   """Compute the trace of a tensor `x`.
1840 
1841   `trace(x)` returns the sum along the main diagonal of each inner-most matrix
1842   in x. If x is of rank `k` with shape `[I, J, K, ..., L, M, N]`, then output
1843   is a tensor of rank `k-2` with dimensions `[I, J, K, ..., L]` where
1844 
1845   `output[i, j, k, ..., l] = trace(x[i, j, i, ..., l, :, :])`
1846 
1847   For example:
1848 
1849   ```python
1850   x = tf.constant([[1, 2], [3, 4]])
1851   tf.linalg.trace(x)  # 5
1852 
1853   x = tf.constant([[1, 2, 3],
1854                    [4, 5, 6],
1855                    [7, 8, 9]])
1856   tf.linalg.trace(x)  # 15
1857 
1858   x = tf.constant([[[1, 2, 3],
1859                     [4, 5, 6],
1860                     [7, 8, 9]],
1861                    [[-1, -2, -3],
1862                     [-4, -5, -6],
1863                     [-7, -8, -9]]])
1864   tf.linalg.trace(x)  # [15, -15]
1865   ```
1866 
1867   Args:
1868     x: tensor.
1869     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1870 
1871   Returns:
1872     The trace of input tensor.
1873   """
1874   with ops.name_scope(name, "Trace", [x]) as name:
1875     x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
1876     return reduce_sum(array_ops.matrix_diag_part(x), [-1], name=name)

1879 @tf_export("linalg.matmul", "matmul")
1880 def matmul(a,
1881            b,
1882            transpose_a=False,
1883            transpose_b=False,
1884            adjoint_a=False,
1885            adjoint_b=False,
1886            a_is_sparse=False,
1887            b_is_sparse=False,
1888            name=None):
1889   """Multiplies matrix `a` by matrix `b`, producing `a` * `b`.
1890 
1891   The inputs must, following any transpositions, be tensors of rank >= 2
1892   where the inner 2 dimensions specify valid matrix multiplication arguments,
1893   and any further outer dimensions match.
1894 
1895   Both matrices must be of the same type. The supported types are:
1896   `float16`, `float32`, `float64`, `int32`, `complex64`, `complex128`.
1897 
1898   Either matrix can be transposed or adjointed (conjugated and transposed) on
1899   the fly by setting one of the corresponding flag to `True`. These are `False`
1900   by default.
1901 
1902   If one or both of the matrices contain a lot of zeros, a more efficient
1903   multiplication algorithm can be used by setting the corresponding
1904   `a_is_sparse` or `b_is_sparse` flag to `True`. These are `False` by default.
1905   This optimization is only available for plain matrices (rank-2 tensors) with
1906   datatypes `bfloat16` or `float32`.
1907 
1908   For example:
1909 
1910   ```python
1911   # 2-D tensor `a`
1912   # [[1, 2, 3],
1913   #  [4, 5, 6]]
1914   a = tf.constant([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6], shape=[2, 3])
1915 
1916   # 2-D tensor `b`
1917   # [[ 7,  8],
1918   #  [ 9, 10],
1919   #  [11, 12]]
1920   b = tf.constant([7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12], shape=[3, 2])
1921 
1922   # `a` * `b`
1923   # [[ 58,  64],
1924   #  [139, 154]]
1925   c = tf.matmul(a, b)
1926 
1927 
1928   # 3-D tensor `a`
1929   # [[[ 1,  2,  3],
1930   #   [ 4,  5,  6]],
1931   #  [[ 7,  8,  9],
1932   #   [10, 11, 12]]]
1933   a = tf.constant(np.arange(1, 13, dtype=np.int32),
1934                   shape=[2, 2, 3])
1935 
1936   # 3-D tensor `b`
1937   # [[[13, 14],
1938   #   [15, 16],
1939   #   [17, 18]],
1940   #  [[19, 20],
1941   #   [21, 22],
1942   #   [23, 24]]]
1943   b = tf.constant(np.arange(13, 25, dtype=np.int32),
1944                   shape=[2, 3, 2])
1945 
1946   # `a` * `b`
1947   # [[[ 94, 100],
1948   #   [229, 244]],
1949   #  [[508, 532],
1950   #   [697, 730]]]
1951   c = tf.matmul(a, b)
1952 
1953   # Since python >= 3.5 the @ operator is supported (see PEP 465).
1954   # In TensorFlow, it simply calls the `tf.matmul()` function, so the
1955   # following lines are equivalent:
1956   d = a @ b @ [[10.], [11.]]
1957   d = tf.matmul(tf.matmul(a, b), [[10.], [11.]])
1958   ```
1959 
1960   Args:
1961     a: `Tensor` of type `float16`, `float32`, `float64`, `int32`, `complex64`,
1962       `complex128` and rank > 1.
1963     b: `Tensor` with same type and rank as `a`.
1964     transpose_a: If `True`, `a` is transposed before multiplication.
1965     transpose_b: If `True`, `b` is transposed before multiplication.
1966     adjoint_a: If `True`, `a` is conjugated and transposed before
1967       multiplication.
1968     adjoint_b: If `True`, `b` is conjugated and transposed before
1969       multiplication.
1970     a_is_sparse: If `True`, `a` is treated as a sparse matrix.
1971     b_is_sparse: If `True`, `b` is treated as a sparse matrix.
1972     name: Name for the operation (optional).
1973 
1974   Returns:
1975     A `Tensor` of the same type as `a` and `b` where each inner-most matrix is
1976     the product of the corresponding matrices in `a` and `b`, e.g. if all
1977     transpose or adjoint attributes are `False`:
1978 
1979     `output`[..., i, j] = sum_k (`a`[..., i, k] * `b`[..., k, j]),
1980     for all indices i, j.
1981 
1982     Note: This is matrix product, not element-wise product.
1983 
1984 
1985   Raises:
1986     ValueError: If transpose_a and adjoint_a, or transpose_b and adjoint_b
1987       are both set to True.
1988   """
1989   with ops.name_scope(name, "MatMul", [a, b]) as name:
1990     if transpose_a and adjoint_a:
1991       raise ValueError("Only one of transpose_a and adjoint_a can be True.")
1992     if transpose_b and adjoint_b:
1993       raise ValueError("Only one of transpose_b and adjoint_b can be True.")
1994 
1995     if context.executing_eagerly():
1996       if not isinstance(a, (ops.EagerTensor, _resource_variable_type)):
1997         a = ops.convert_to_tensor(a, name="a")
1998       if not isinstance(b, (ops.EagerTensor, _resource_variable_type)):
1999         b = ops.convert_to_tensor(b, name="b")
2000     else:
2001       a = ops.convert_to_tensor(a, name="a")
2002       b = ops.convert_to_tensor(b, name="b")
2003 
2004     # TODO(apassos) remove _shape_tuple here when it is not needed.
2005     a_shape = a._shape_tuple()  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2006     b_shape = b._shape_tuple()  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2007     if (not a_is_sparse and
2008         not b_is_sparse) and ((a_shape is None or len(a_shape) > 2) and
2009                               (b_shape is None or len(b_shape) > 2)):
2010       # BatchMatmul does not support transpose, so we conjugate the matrix and
2011       # use adjoint instead. Conj() is a noop for real matrices.
2012       if transpose_a:
2013         a = conj(a)
2014         adjoint_a = True
2015       if transpose_b:
2016         b = conj(b)
2017         adjoint_b = True
2018       return gen_math_ops.batch_mat_mul(
2019           a, b, adj_x=adjoint_a, adj_y=adjoint_b, name=name)
2020 
2021     # Neither matmul nor sparse_matmul support adjoint, so we conjugate
2022     # the matrix and use transpose instead. Conj() is a noop for real
2023     # matrices.
2024     if adjoint_a:
2025       a = conj(a)
2026       transpose_a = True
2027     if adjoint_b:
2028       b = conj(b)
2029       transpose_b = True
2030 
2031     use_sparse_matmul = False
2032     if a_is_sparse or b_is_sparse:
2033       sparse_matmul_types = [dtypes.bfloat16, dtypes.float32]
2034       use_sparse_matmul = (
2035           a.dtype in sparse_matmul_types and b.dtype in sparse_matmul_types)
2036     if ((a.dtype == dtypes.bfloat16 or b.dtype == dtypes.bfloat16) and
2037         a.dtype != b.dtype):
2038       # matmul currently doesn't handle mixed-precision inputs.
2039       use_sparse_matmul = True
2040     if use_sparse_matmul:
2041       ret = sparse_matmul(
2042           a,
2043           b,
2044           transpose_a=transpose_a,
2045           transpose_b=transpose_b,
2046           a_is_sparse=a_is_sparse,
2047           b_is_sparse=b_is_sparse,
2048           name=name)
2049       # sparse_matmul always returns float32, even with
2050       # bfloat16 inputs. This prevents us from configuring bfloat16 training.
2051       # casting to bfloat16 also matches non-sparse matmul behavior better.
2052       if a.dtype == dtypes.bfloat16 and b.dtype == dtypes.bfloat16:
2053         ret = cast(ret, dtypes.bfloat16)
2054       return ret
2055     else:
2056       return gen_math_ops.mat_mul(
2057           a, b, transpose_a=transpose_a, transpose_b=transpose_b, name=name)
2058

2082 def _as_indexed_slices(x, optimize=True):
2083   """Convert 'x' to IndexedSlices.
2084 
2085   Convert a dense Tensor to a block-sparse IndexedSlices.
2086 
2087   Args:
2088     x: Either a Tensor object, or an IndexedSlices object.
2089     optimize: if true, attempt to optimize the conversion of 'x'.
2090 
2091   Returns:
2092     An IndexedSlices object.
2093 
2094   Raises:
2095     TypeError: If 'x' is not a Tensor or an IndexedSlices object.
2096   """
2097   # TODO(touts): op_scope
2098   if not isinstance(x, (ops.Tensor, ops.IndexedSlices)):
2099     raise TypeError("Not a Tensor or IndexedSlices: %s" % type(x))
2100   if isinstance(x, ops.IndexedSlices):
2101     return x
2102   x_shape = array_ops.shape_internal(x, optimize=optimize)
2103   return ops.IndexedSlices(x, range(0, x_shape[0]), x_shape)

2106 def _as_indexed_slices_list(inputs, optimize=True):
2107   """Convert all elements of 'inputs' to IndexedSlices.
2108 
2109   Additionally, homogenize the types of all the indices to
2110   either int32 or int64.
2111 
2112   Args:
2113     inputs: List containing either Tensor or IndexedSlices objects.
2114     optimize: if true, attempt to optimize the conversion of each input.
2115 
2116   Returns:
2117     A list of IndexedSlices objects.
2118 
2119   Raises:
2120     TypeError: If 'inputs' is not a list or a tuple.
2121   """
2122   if not isinstance(inputs, (list, tuple)):
2123     raise TypeError("Expected a list or tuple, not a %s" % type(inputs))
2124   outputs = [_as_indexed_slices(i, optimize=optimize) for i in inputs]
2125   with_int32_index = [
2126       o.indices for o in outputs if o.indices.dtype == dtypes.int32
2127   ]
2128   if not with_int32_index or len(with_int32_index) == len(outputs):
2129     return outputs
2130   casted_outputs = []
2131   for o in outputs:
2132     if o.indices.dtype == dtypes.int32:
2133       casted_outputs.append(
2134           ops.IndexedSlices(o.values, cast(o.indices, dtypes.int64),
2135                             o.dense_shape))
2136     else:
2137       casted_outputs.append(o)
2138   return casted_outputs

2176 @tf_export("math.accumulate_n", "accumulate_n")
2177 @deprecation.deprecated_endpoints("accumulate_n")
2178 def accumulate_n(inputs, shape=None, tensor_dtype=None, name=None):
2179   """Returns the element-wise sum of a list of tensors.
2180 
2181   Optionally, pass `shape` and `tensor_dtype` for shape and type checking,
2182   otherwise, these are inferred.
2183 
2184   `tf.math.accumulate_n` performs the same operation as `tf.add_n`, but does not
2185   wait for all of its inputs to be ready before beginning to sum. This can
2186   save memory if inputs are ready at different times, since minimum temporary
2187   storage is proportional to the output size rather than the inputs size.
2188 
2189   `accumulate_n` is differentiable (but wasn't previous to TensorFlow 1.7).
2190 
2191   For example:
2192 
2193   ```python
2194   a = tf.constant([[1, 2], [3, 4]])
2195   b = tf.constant([[5, 0], [0, 6]])
2196   tf.math.accumulate_n([a, b, a])  # [[7, 4], [6, 14]]
2197 
2198   # Explicitly pass shape and type
2199   tf.math.accumulate_n([a, b, a], shape=[2, 2], tensor_dtype=tf.int32)
2200                                                                  # [[7,  4],
2201                                                                  #  [6, 14]]
2202   ```
2203 
2204   Args:
2205     inputs: A list of `Tensor` objects, each with same shape and type.
2206     shape: Shape of elements of `inputs`.
2207     tensor_dtype: The type of `inputs`.
2208     name: A name for the operation (optional).
2209 
2210   Returns:
2211     A `Tensor` of same shape and type as the elements of `inputs`.
2212 
2213   Raises:
2214     ValueError: If `inputs` don't all have same shape and dtype or the shape
2215     cannot be inferred.
2216   """
2217 
2218   def _input_error():
2219     return ValueError("inputs must be a list of at least one Tensor with the "
2220                       "same dtype and shape")
2221 
2222   if not inputs or not isinstance(inputs, (list, tuple)):
2223     raise _input_error()
2224   inputs = ops.convert_n_to_tensor_or_indexed_slices(inputs)
2225   if not all(isinstance(x, ops.Tensor) for x in inputs):
2226     raise _input_error()
2227   if not all(x.dtype == inputs[0].dtype for x in inputs):
2228     raise _input_error()
2229   if shape is not None:
2230     shape = tensor_shape.as_shape(shape)
2231   else:
2232     shape = tensor_shape.unknown_shape()
2233   for input_tensor in inputs:
2234     if isinstance(input_tensor, ops.Tensor):
2235       shape = shape.merge_with(input_tensor.get_shape())
2236 
2237   # tensor_dtype is for safety only; operator's output type computed in C++
2238   if tensor_dtype is not None and tensor_dtype != inputs[0].dtype:
2239     raise TypeError("tensor_dtype is {}, but input is of type {}".format(
2240         tensor_dtype, inputs[0].dtype))
2241 
2242   if len(inputs) == 1 and name is None:
2243     return inputs[0]
2244   elif len(inputs) == 1 and name is not None:
2245     return array_ops.identity(inputs[0], name=name)
2246   elif context.executing_eagerly():
2247     # TemporaryVariable not currently supported in eager mode; fall back
2248     # onto AddN for now.
2249     # TODO(frreiss) remove this once the lifetime of eager variables gets
2250     # addressed
2251     return add_n(inputs, name=name)
2252   else:
2253     return gen_math_ops.accumulate_nv2(inputs, name=name, shape=shape)  # pylint: disable=protected-access

2263 @tf_export("math.sigmoid", "nn.sigmoid", "sigmoid")
2264 def sigmoid(x, name=None):
2265   """Computes sigmoid of `x` element-wise.
2266 
2267   Specifically, `y = 1 / (1 + exp(-x))`.
2268 
2269   Args:
2270     x: A Tensor with type `float16`, `float32`, `float64`, `complex64`,
2271       or `complex128`.
2272     name: A name for the operation (optional).

2327 @tf_export("math.bincount", "bincount")
2328 @deprecation.deprecated_endpoints("bincount")
2329 def bincount(arr,
2330              weights=None,
2331              minlength=None,
2332              maxlength=None,
2333              dtype=dtypes.int32):
2334   """Counts the number of occurrences of each value in an integer array.
2335 
2336   If `minlength` and `maxlength` are not given, returns a vector with length
2337   `tf.reduce_max(arr) + 1` if `arr` is non-empty, and length 0 otherwise.
2338   If `weights` are non-None, then index `i` of the output stores the sum of the
2339   value in `weights` at each index where the corresponding value in `arr` is
2340   `i`.
2341 
2342   Args:
2343     arr: An int32 tensor of non-negative values.
2344     weights: If non-None, must be the same shape as arr. For each value in
2345         `arr`, the bin will be incremented by the corresponding weight instead
2346         of 1.
2347     minlength: If given, ensures the output has length at least `minlength`,
2348         padding with zeros at the end if necessary.
2349     maxlength: If given, skips values in `arr` that are equal or greater than
2350         `maxlength`, ensuring that the output has length at most `maxlength`.
2351     dtype: If `weights` is None, determines the type of the output bins.
2352 
2353   Returns:
2354     A vector with the same dtype as `weights` or the given `dtype`. The bin
2355     values.
2356   """
2357   arr = ops.convert_to_tensor(arr, name="arr", dtype=dtypes.int32)
2358   array_is_nonempty = reduce_prod(array_ops.shape(arr)) > 0
2359   output_size = cast(array_is_nonempty, dtypes.int32) * (reduce_max(arr) + 1)
2360   if minlength is not None:
2361     minlength = ops.convert_to_tensor(
2362         minlength, name="minlength", dtype=dtypes.int32)
2363     output_size = gen_math_ops.maximum(minlength, output_size)
2364   if maxlength is not None:
2365     maxlength = ops.convert_to_tensor(
2366         maxlength, name="maxlength", dtype=dtypes.int32)
2367     output_size = gen_math_ops.minimum(maxlength, output_size)
2368   if weights is not None:
2369     weights = ops.convert_to_tensor(weights, name="weights")
2370     return gen_math_ops.unsorted_segment_sum(weights, arr, output_size)
2371   weights = constant_op.constant([], dtype)
2372   return gen_math_ops.bincount(arr, output_size, weights)

2375 @tf_export("math.cumsum", "cumsum")
2376 def cumsum(x, axis=0, exclusive=False, reverse=False, name=None):
2377   """Compute the cumulative sum of the tensor `x` along `axis`.
2378 
2379   By default, this op performs an inclusive cumsum, which means that the first
2380   element of the input is identical to the first element of the output:
2381 
2382   ```python
2383   tf.cumsum([a, b, c])  # [a, a + b, a + b + c]
2384   ```
2385 
2386   By setting the `exclusive` kwarg to `True`, an exclusive cumsum is performed
2387   instead:
2388 
2389   ```python
2390   tf.cumsum([a, b, c], exclusive=True)  # [0, a, a + b]
2391   ```
2392 
2393   By setting the `reverse` kwarg to `True`, the cumsum is performed in the
2394   opposite direction:
2395 
2396   ```python
2397   tf.cumsum([a, b, c], reverse=True)  # [a + b + c, b + c, c]
2398   ```
2399 
2400   This is more efficient than using separate `tf.reverse` ops.
2401 
2402   The `reverse` and `exclusive` kwargs can also be combined:
2403 
2404   ```python
2405   tf.cumsum([a, b, c], exclusive=True, reverse=True)  # [b + c, c, 0]
2406   ```
2407 
2408   Args:
2409     x: A `Tensor`. Must be one of the following types: `float32`, `float64`,
2410        `int64`, `int32`, `uint8`, `uint16`, `int16`, `int8`, `complex64`,
2411        `complex128`, `qint8`, `quint8`, `qint32`, `half`.
2412     axis: A `Tensor` of type `int32` (default: 0). Must be in the range
2413       `[-rank(x), rank(x))`.
2414     exclusive: If `True`, perform exclusive cumsum.
2415     reverse: A `bool` (default: False).
2416     name: A name for the operation (optional).
2417 
2418   Returns:
2419     A `Tensor`. Has the same type as `x`.
2420   """
2421   with ops.name_scope(name, "Cumsum", [x]) as name:
2422     x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
2423     return gen_math_ops.cumsum(
2424         x, axis, exclusive=exclusive, reverse=reverse, name=name)

2480 @tf_export("math.conj", "conj")

2483   r"""Returns the complex conjugate of a complex number.
2484 
2485   Given a tensor `input` of complex numbers, this operation returns a tensor of
2486   complex numbers that are the complex conjugate of each element in `input`. The
2487   complex numbers in `input` must be of the form \\(a + bj\\), where *a* is the
2488   real part and *b* is the imaginary part.
2489

2491

2493

2500     x: `Tensor` to conjugate.  Must have numeric or variant type.
2501     name: A name for the operation (optional).
2502

2504     A `Tensor` that is the conjugate of `x` (with the same type).
2505 
2506   Raises:
2507     TypeError: If `x` is not a numeric tensor.
2508   """
2509   if isinstance(x, ops.Tensor):
2510     dt = x.dtype
2511     if dt.is_floating or dt.is_integer:
2512       return x
2513   with ops.name_scope(name, "Conj", [x]) as name:
2514     x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
2515     if x.dtype.is_complex or x.dtype == dtypes.variant:
2516       return gen_math_ops.conj(x, name=name)
2517     elif x.dtype.is_floating or x.dtype.is_integer:
2518       return x
2519     else:
2520       raise TypeError(
2521           "Expected numeric or variant tensor, got dtype %r" % x.dtype)

2532 def reduced_shape(input_shape, axes):
2533   """Helper function for reduction ops.
2534 
2535   Args:
2536     input_shape: 1-D Tensor, the shape of the Tensor being reduced.
2537     axes: 1-D Tensor, the reduction axes.
2538   Returns:
2539     A 1-D Tensor, the output shape as if keepdims were set to True.
2540   """
2541   # Example:
2542   # cast needed for SparseTensor reductions
2543   if context.executing_eagerly():
2544     input_shape = input_shape.numpy()
2545     axes = axes.numpy()
2546     input_shape[axes] = 1
2547     return input_shape
2548 
2549   input_shape = to_int32(input_shape)  # [2, 3, 5, 7]
2550   axes = to_int32(axes)  # [1, 2]
2551 
2552   input_rank = array_ops.size(input_shape)  # 4
2553   axes = (axes + input_rank) % input_rank
2554   axes_shape = array_ops.shape(axes)  # [2]
2555   return gen_data_flow_ops.dynamic_stitch(  # [2, 1, 1, 7]
2556       [
2557           range(input_rank),  # [0, 1, 2, 3]
2558           axes
2559       ],  # [1, 2]
2560       [
2561           input_shape,  # [2, 3, 5, 7]
2562           array_ops.fill(axes_shape, 1)
2563       ])  # [1, 1]

2566 def _unsorted_segment_N(data, segment_ids, num_segments):
2567   """ Helper function for unsorted_segment_mean/_sqrtN. Computes the number
2568       of segment entries with 0-entries set to 1 to allow division by N.
2569   """
2570   # bincount doesn't support negative indices so we use unsorted_segment_sum
2571   segment_ids_shape = array_ops.shape_internal(segment_ids)
2572   ones_tensor = array_ops.ones(segment_ids_shape, dtype=data.dtype)
2573   N = gen_math_ops.unsorted_segment_sum(ones_tensor, segment_ids, num_segments)
2574   # add dimensions for all non-reduced axes
2575   ndims_output = data.shape.ndims - segment_ids.shape.ndims
2576   broadcast_shape = [num_segments] + [1] * ndims_output
2577   N = array_ops.reshape(N, broadcast_shape)
2578   return gen_math_ops.maximum(N, 1)

2581 @tf_export("math.unsorted_segment_mean", "unsorted_segment_mean")
2582 @deprecation.deprecated_endpoints("unsorted_segment_mean")
2583 def unsorted_segment_mean(data, segment_ids, num_segments, name=None):
2584   r"""Computes the mean along segments of a tensor.
2585 
2586   Read [the section on
2587   segmentation](https://tensorflow.org/api_guides/python/math_ops#segmentation)
2588   for an explanation of segments.
2589 
2590   This operator is similar to the unsorted segment sum operator found
2591   [here](../../../api_docs/python/math_ops.md#UnsortedSegmentSum).
2592   Instead of computing the sum over segments, it computes the mean of all
2593   entries belonging to a segment such that:
2594 
2595   \\(output_i = 1/N_i \sum_{j...} data[j...]\\) where the sum is over tuples
2596   `j...` such that `segment_ids[j...] == i` with \\N_i\\ being the number of
2597   occurrences of id \\i\\.
2598 
2599   If there is no entry for a given segment ID `i`, it outputs 0.
2600 
2601   If the given segment ID `i` is negative, the value is dropped and will not
2602   be added to the sum of the segment.
2603 
2604   Args:
2605     data: A `Tensor` with floating point or complex dtype.
2606     segment_ids: An integer tensor whose shape is a prefix of `data.shape`.
2607     num_segments: An integer scalar `Tensor`.  The number of distinct
2608       segment IDs.
2609     name: A name for the operation (optional).
2610 
2611   Returns:
2612     A `Tensor`.  Has same shape as data, except for the first `segment_ids.rank`
2613     dimensions, which are replaced with a single dimension which has size
2614    `num_segments`.
2615   """
2616   with ops.name_scope(name, "UnsortedSegmentMean"):
2617     data = ops.convert_to_tensor(data)
2618     segment_ids = ops.convert_to_tensor(segment_ids)
2619     N = _unsorted_segment_N(data, segment_ids, num_segments)
2620     summed = gen_math_ops.unsorted_segment_sum(data, segment_ids, num_segments)
2621     return summed / N

2670 @tf_export("sparse.segment_sum", "sparse_segment_sum")
2671 @deprecation.deprecated_endpoints("sparse_segment_sum")
2672 def sparse_segment_sum(data, indices, segment_ids, name=None,
2673                        num_segments=None):
2674   r"""Computes the sum along sparse segments of a tensor.
2675 
2676   Read [the section on
2677   segmentation](https://tensorflow.org/api_guides/python/math_ops#Segmentation)
2678   for an explanation of segments.
2679 
2680   Like `SegmentSum`, but `segment_ids` can have rank less than `data`'s first
2681   dimension, selecting a subset of dimension 0, specified by `indices`.
2682   `segment_ids` is allowed to have missing ids, in which case the output will
2683   be zeros at those indices. In those cases `num_segments` is used to determine
2684   the size of the output.
2685 
2686   For example:
2687 
2688   ```python
2689   c = tf.constant([[1,2,3,4], [-1,-2,-3,-4], [5,6,7,8]])
2690 
2691   # Select two rows, one segment.
2692   tf.sparse.segment_sum(c, tf.constant([0, 1]), tf.constant([0, 0]))
2693   # => [[0 0 0 0]]
2694 
2695   # Select two rows, two segment.
2696   tf.sparse.segment_sum(c, tf.constant([0, 1]), tf.constant([0, 1]))
2697   # => [[ 1  2  3  4]
2698   #     [-1 -2 -3 -4]]
2699 
2700   # With missing segment ids.
2701   tf.sparse.segment_sum(c, tf.constant([0, 1]), tf.constant([0, 2]),
2702                         num_segments=4)
2703   # => [[ 1  2  3  4]
2704   #     [ 0  0  0  0]
2705   #     [-1 -2 -3 -4]
2706   #     [ 0  0  0  0]]
2707 
2708   # Select all rows, two segments.
2709   tf.sparse.segment_sum(c, tf.constant([0, 1, 2]), tf.constant([0, 0, 1]))
2710   # => [[0 0 0 0]
2711   #     [5 6 7 8]]
2712 
2713   # Which is equivalent to:
2714   tf.segment_sum(c, tf.constant([0, 0, 1]))
2715   ```
2716 
2717   Args:
2718     data: A `Tensor` with data that will be assembled in the output.
2719     indices: A 1-D `Tensor` with indices into `data`. Has same rank as
2720       `segment_ids`.
2721     segment_ids: A 1-D `Tensor` with indices into the output `Tensor`.
2722       Values should be sorted and can be repeated.
2723     name: A name for the operation (optional).
2724     num_segments: An optional int32 scalar. Indicates the size of the output
2725       `Tensor`.
2726 
2727   Returns:
2728     A `tensor` of the shape as data, except for dimension 0 which
2729     has size `k`, the number of segments specified via `num_segments` or
2730     inferred for the last element in `segments_ids`.
2731   """
2732   if num_segments is not None:
2733     return gen_math_ops.sparse_segment_sum_with_num_segments(
2734         data=data,
2735         indices=indices,
2736         segment_ids=segment_ids,
2737         num_segments=num_segments,
2738         name=name)
2739   else:
2740     return gen_math_ops.sparse_segment_sum(
2741         data=data, indices=indices, segment_ids=segment_ids, name=name)

2823   else:
2824     return gen_math_ops.sparse_segment_sqrt_n(
2825         data=data, indices=indices, segment_ids=segment_ids, name=name)

2828 @tf_export("tensordot", "linalg.tensordot")
2829 def tensordot(a, b, axes, name=None):
2830   r"""Tensor contraction of a and b along specified axes.
2831 
2832   Tensordot (also known as tensor contraction) sums the product of elements
2833   from `a` and `b` over the indices specified by `a_axes` and `b_axes`.
2834   The lists `a_axes` and `b_axes` specify those pairs of axes along which to
2835   contract the tensors. The axis `a_axes[i]` of `a` must have the same dimension
2836   as axis `b_axes[i]` of `b` for all `i` in `range(0, len(a_axes))`. The lists
2837   `a_axes` and `b_axes` must have identical length and consist of unique
2838   integers that specify valid axes for each of the tensors.
2839 
2840   This operation corresponds to `numpy.tensordot(a, b, axes)`.
2841 
2842   Example 1: When `a` and `b` are matrices (order 2), the case `axes = 1`
2843   is equivalent to matrix multiplication.
2844 
2845   Example 2: When `a` and `b` are matrices (order 2), the case
2846   `axes = [[1], [0]]` is equivalent to matrix multiplication.
2847 
2848   Example 3: Suppose that \\(a_{ijk}\\) and \\(b_{lmn}\\) represent two
2849   tensors of order 3. Then, `contract(a, b, [[0], [2]])` is the order 4 tensor
2850   \\(c_{jklm}\\) whose entry
2851   corresponding to the indices \\((j,k,l,m)\\) is given by:
2852 
2853   \\( c_{jklm} = \sum_i a_{ijk} b_{lmi} \\).
2854 
2855   In general, `order(c) = order(a) + order(b) - 2*len(axes[0])`.
2856 
2857   Args:
2858     a: `Tensor` of type `float32` or `float64`.
2859     b: `Tensor` with the same type as `a`.
2860     axes: Either a scalar `N`, or a list or an `int32` `Tensor` of shape [2, k].
2861      If axes is a scalar, sum over the last N axes of a and the first N axes
2862      of b in order.
2863      If axes is a list or `Tensor` the first and second row contain the set of
2864      unique integers specifying axes along which the contraction is computed,
2865      for `a` and `b`, respectively. The number of axes for `a` and `b` must
2866      be equal.
2867     name: A name for the operation (optional).
2868 
2869   Returns:
2870     A `Tensor` with the same type as `a`.
2871 
2872   Raises:
2873     ValueError: If the shapes of `a`, `b`, and `axes` are incompatible.
2874     IndexError: If the values in axes exceed the rank of the corresponding
2875       tensor.
2876   """
2877 
2878   def _tensordot_reshape(a, axes, flipped=False):
2879     """Helper method to perform transpose and reshape for contraction op.
2880 
2881     This method is helpful in reducing `math_ops.tensordot` to `math_ops.matmul`
2882     using `array_ops.transpose` and `array_ops.reshape`. The method takes a
2883     tensor and performs the correct transpose and reshape operation for a given
2884     set of indices. It returns the reshaped tensor as well as a list of indices
2885     necessary to reshape the tensor again after matrix multiplication.
2886 
2887     Args:
2888       a: `Tensor`.
2889       axes: List or `int32` `Tensor` of unique indices specifying valid axes of
2890        `a`.
2891       flipped: An optional `bool`. Defaults to `False`. If `True`, the method
2892         assumes that `a` is the second argument in the contraction operation.
2893 
2894     Returns:
2895       A tuple `(reshaped_a, free_dims, free_dims_static)` where `reshaped_a` is
2896       the tensor `a` reshaped to allow contraction via `matmul`, `free_dims` is
2897       either a list of integers or an `int32` `Tensor`, depending on whether
2898       the shape of a is fully specified, and free_dims_static is either a list
2899       of integers and None values, or None, representing the inferred
2900       static shape of the free dimensions
2901     """
2902     if a.get_shape().is_fully_defined() and isinstance(axes, (list, tuple)):
2903       shape_a = a.get_shape().as_list()
2904       axes = [i if i >= 0 else i + len(shape_a) for i in axes]
2905       free = [i for i in xrange(len(shape_a)) if i not in axes]
2906       free_dims = [shape_a[i] for i in free]
2907       prod_free = int(np.prod([shape_a[i] for i in free]))
2908       prod_axes = int(np.prod([shape_a[i] for i in axes]))
2909       perm = list(axes) + free if flipped else free + list(axes)
2910       new_shape = [prod_axes, prod_free] if flipped else [prod_free, prod_axes]
2911       reshaped_a = array_ops.reshape(array_ops.transpose(a, perm), new_shape)
2912       return reshaped_a, free_dims, free_dims
2913     else:
2914       if a.get_shape().ndims is not None and isinstance(axes, (list, tuple)):
2915         shape_a = a.get_shape().as_list()
2916         axes = [i if i >= 0 else i + len(shape_a) for i in axes]
2917         free = [i for i in xrange(len(shape_a)) if i not in axes]
2918         axes_dims = [shape_a[i] for i in axes]
2919         free_dims = [shape_a[i] for i in free]
2920         free_dims_static = free_dims
2921         axes = ops.convert_to_tensor(axes, dtype=dtypes.int32, name="axes")
2922         free = ops.convert_to_tensor(free, dtype=dtypes.int32, name="free")
2923         shape_a = array_ops.shape(a)
2924       else:
2925         free_dims_static = None
2926         shape_a = array_ops.shape(a)
2927         rank_a = array_ops.rank(a)
2928         axes = ops.convert_to_tensor(axes, dtype=dtypes.int32, name="axes")
2929         axes = array_ops.where(axes >= 0, axes, axes + rank_a)
2930         free, _ = array_ops.setdiff1d(range(rank_a), axes)
2931       free_dims = array_ops.gather(shape_a, free)
2932       axes_dims = array_ops.gather(shape_a, axes)
2933       prod_free_dims = reduce_prod(free_dims)
2934       prod_axes_dims = reduce_prod(axes_dims)
2935       if flipped:
2936         perm = array_ops.concat([axes, free], 0)
2937         new_shape = array_ops.stack([prod_axes_dims, prod_free_dims])
2938       else:
2939         perm = array_ops.concat([free, axes], 0)
2940         new_shape = array_ops.stack([prod_free_dims, prod_axes_dims])
2941       reshaped_a = array_ops.reshape(array_ops.transpose(a, perm), new_shape)
2942       return reshaped_a, free_dims, free_dims_static
2943 
2944   def _tensordot_axes(a, axes):
2945     """Generates two sets of contraction axes for the two tensor arguments."""
2946     a_shape = a.get_shape()
2947     if isinstance(axes, compat.integral_types):
2948       if axes < 0:
2949         raise ValueError("'axes' must be at least 0.")
2950       if a_shape.ndims is not None:
2951         if axes > a_shape.ndims:
2952           raise ValueError("'axes' must not be larger than the number of "
2953                            "dimensions of tensor %s." % a)
2954         return (list(xrange(a_shape.ndims - axes, a_shape.ndims)),
2955                 list(xrange(axes)))
2956       else:
2957         rank = array_ops.rank(a)
2958         return (range(rank - axes, rank, dtype=dtypes.int32),
2959                 range(axes, dtype=dtypes.int32))
2960     elif isinstance(axes, (list, tuple)):
2961       if len(axes) != 2:
2962         raise ValueError("'axes' must be an integer or have length 2.")
2963       a_axes = axes[0]
2964       b_axes = axes[1]
2965       if isinstance(a_axes, compat.integral_types) and \
2966           isinstance(b_axes, compat.integral_types):
2967         a_axes = [a_axes]
2968         b_axes = [b_axes]
2969       if len(a_axes) != len(b_axes):
2970         raise ValueError(
2971             "Different number of contraction axes 'a' and 'b', %s != %s." %
2972             (len(a_axes), len(b_axes)))
2973       return a_axes, b_axes
2974     else:
2975       axes = ops.convert_to_tensor(axes, name="axes", dtype=dtypes.int32)
2976       return axes[0], axes[1]
2977 
2978   with ops.name_scope(name, "Tensordot", [a, b, axes]) as name:
2979     a = ops.convert_to_tensor(a, name="a")
2980     b = ops.convert_to_tensor(b, name="b")
2981     a_axes, b_axes = _tensordot_axes(a, axes)
2982     a_reshape, a_free_dims, a_free_dims_static = _tensordot_reshape(a, a_axes)
2983     b_reshape, b_free_dims, b_free_dims_static = _tensordot_reshape(
2984         b, b_axes, True)
2985     ab_matmul = matmul(a_reshape, b_reshape)
2986     if isinstance(a_free_dims, list) and isinstance(b_free_dims, list):
2987       return array_ops.reshape(ab_matmul, a_free_dims + b_free_dims, name=name)
2988     else:
2989       a_free_dims = ops.convert_to_tensor(a_free_dims, dtype=dtypes.int32)
2990       b_free_dims = ops.convert_to_tensor(b_free_dims, dtype=dtypes.int32)
2991       product = array_ops.reshape(
2992           ab_matmul, array_ops.concat([a_free_dims, b_free_dims], 0), name=name)
2993       if a_free_dims_static is not None and b_free_dims_static is not None:
2994         product.set_shape(a_free_dims_static + b_free_dims_static)
2995       return product

2998 @tf_export("math.polyval")
2999 def polyval(coeffs, x, name=None):
3000   r"""Computes the elementwise value of a polynomial.
3001 
3002   If `x` is a tensor and `coeffs` is a list n + 1 tensors, this function returns
3003   the value of the n-th order polynomial
3004 
3005      p(x) = coeffs[n-1] + coeffs[n-2] * x + ...  + coeffs[0] * x**(n-1)
3006 
3007   evaluated using Horner's method, i.e.
3008 
3009      p(x) = coeffs[n-1] + x * (coeffs[n-2] + ... + x * (coeffs[1] +
3010             x * coeffs[0]))
3011 
3012   Args:
3013     coeffs: A list of `Tensor` representing the coefficients of the polynomial.
3014     x: A `Tensor` representing the variable of the polynomial.
3015     name: A name for the operation (optional).
3016 
3017   Returns:
3018     A `tensor` of the shape as the expression p(x) with usual broadcasting rules
3019     for element-wise addition and multiplication applied.
3020 
3021   @compatibility(numpy)
3022   Equivalent to numpy.polyval.
3023   @end_compatibility
3024   """
3025 
3026   with ops.name_scope(name, "polyval", nest.flatten(coeffs) + [x]) as name:
3027     x = ops.convert_to_tensor(x, name="x")
3028     if len(coeffs) < 1:
3029       return array_ops.zeros_like(x, name=name)
3030     coeffs = [
3031         ops.convert_to_tensor(coeff, name=("coeff_%d" % index))
3032         for index, coeff in enumerate(coeffs)
3033     ]
3034     p = coeffs[0]
3035     for c in coeffs[1:]:
3036       p = c + p * x
3037     return p
